{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:31:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:31:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12442"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12442"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.14,0.18,0.07,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4950"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77761"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4950"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63277"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"9640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8206"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77761"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents with a one-month history of fatigue, joint pain and irritability. She also reports that she has become quite irritable lately for no clear reason. Prior to this she had been in good health with no significant medical illnesses. She does not smoke or drink. She is not taking any medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 128/84 mmHg, pulse 76/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her BMI is 21. She has a brownish ring around her cornea. Her liver edge is palpable. Her liver function tests are shown (Image). Her ceruloplasmin is 0.015 g/L (0.24-0.60) and 24-hour-urinary copper is 1.5 \u03bcmol/24h. (0.3-0.8 \u03bcmol/24h.).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Penicillamine","Deferoxamine","Zinc acetate","Trientine","EDTA"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms of this patient, accompanied by the laboratory results are suggestive of Wilson disease, a rare autosomal recessive inherited disorder of copper metabolism that is characterised by excessive deposition of copper in the liver, brain, and other tissues. The incidence of this disease in Australia is 1 case per 100,000 population. The treatment of choice in this case would be \u003Cstrong\u003Epenicillamine. \u003C/strong\u003EThis decreases the amount of copper that is accumulating in the liver and other organs by working as a chelating agent for copper and assisting its excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrientine \u003C/strong\u003Eis also an effective treatment option for Wilson disease but is usually the second line option where penicillamine is contra-indicated like in allergic patient or lactating women etc. It is also a chelating agent that binds to excess copper and removes it from the blood stream.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZinc acetate \u003C/strong\u003Eis used as a maintenance therapy for Wilson disease by induction of intestinal cell metallothionein, which blocks copper absorption from the intestinal track thereby reducing the excessive copper in the body. It is usually used as an adjunct to the chelating agents rather than a standalone therapy as they are more effective and prevent hepatic deterioration in individuals with Wilson disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEDTA (Ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a chelating agent used in the management and treatment of heavy metal toxicity like lead, iron or mercury. It has not been effective in copper chelation making it a least likely choice for someone with Wilson disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeferoxamine \u003C/strong\u003Eis used to treat iron overload by working as a chelating agent for iron. It has no role in the treatment of this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Penicillamine is the treatment of choice in Wilson disease."],"references":["Schilsky ML. Wilson Disease: Diagnosis, Treatment, and Follow-up. Clin Liver Dis. 2017 Nov;21(4):755-767. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2017.06.011. Epub 2017 Aug 10. PMID: 28987261. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28987261/","Kasztelan-Szczerbinska B, Cichoz-Lach H. Wilson\u0027s Disease: An Update on the Diagnostic Workup and Management. J Clin Med. 2021 Oct 30;10(21):5097. doi: 10.3390/jcm10215097. PMID: 34768617; PMCID: PMC8584493. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8584493/","Immergluck J, Anilkumar AC. Wilson Disease. 2023 Aug 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28723019. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28723019/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63277"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12442"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19597"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19597"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ed7ee105-502c-4758-8576-ca181e0139db.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ed7ee105-502c-4758-8576-ca181e0139db.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":856,"height":6